[What's new in this report is that the offspring are coming down with
the disease after all the parents died. I'm going to stick my neck out
on this one. To me it's obvious that the infection is not sand fly
transmitted, because only foxhounds are coming down with it -- if it's
carried by sand flies, why aren´t other breeds living nearby, which
they
certainly also feed on, coming down with it? Why should foxhounds be
uniquely
susceptible?
My hypothesis is that some foxhounds were sent to the Middle East,
perhaps to a dog show, & became infected there by sand fly bite before
returning to the USA. Foxhounds have a unique ecology in that they
live in packs & are often exchanged between hunts, which give perfect
opportunities for the spread of disease. Following the observation in
a previous post in this thread that visceral leishmaniasis can be
transmitted in humans sexually and congenitally as well as by sand fly
bite, the same thing could be occurring with the foxhounds. Meaning
that there is no threat to human health. - Mod.JW
................................tg/pg/jw
